### 3) A short story: the three little pigs meet Little Red Riding Hood
On a bright morning, the three little pigs were hard at work. The first pig, Straw, was weaving a roof of golden straw. The second pig, Stick, was stacking twigs into neat walls. The third pig, Brick, was laying heavy bricks and humming to himself.

A rustle came from the path. A girl in a red cloak appeared, carrying a basket. “Good morning,” she said. “I’m Little Red Riding Hood. I’m taking cake to my grandmother.”

The pigs paused. “Be careful,” said Straw. “There’s a wolf about.”

“I know,” said Red. “He tried to trick me once. I outsmarted him.”

Just then, a shadow fell. The wolf slunk into the clearing, eyes gleaming. “Little pig, little pig,” he growled, “let me come in.”

“Not by the hair of my chinny-chin-chin,” Brick declared.

The wolf huffed and puffed at Straw’s house. It collapsed in a swirl. Straw and Stick ran to Brick’s sturdy door. Red stepped behind them, clutching her basket.

The wolf lunged at Brick’s house, but the bricks held firm. He huffed and puffed until his cheeks ached. Then he tried the chimney. Brick had a pot of soup boiling below. The wolf dropped into it with a sizzle and a yelp, scrambled out, and fled into the woods, vowing never to bother pigs again.

Red thanked the pigs and offered them cake. They shared it under the shade of an oak, laughing at how a wolf’s greed had met its match. From that day on, the pigs and Red kept watch for each other, and the forest felt a little safer. [end of text]


